<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5> when the band begins to play • when the fat lady sings</xh5><p> <i>when the band begins to play</i>—(coll.) when matters become very serious or critical: ...they are supplied with the best of weapons. Naturally only the best is good enough <u>when the band begins to play</u>.</p><p> <i>when the fat lady sings</i>—(U.S. sl.) when smth. is finally concluded; at the end of a match, performance, etc.: We can leave with everybody else <u>when the fat lady sings</u>.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> Neither expression correlates in meaning with the phrase <b>when one’s ship comes home</b>—when one comes into money: The other guests on our table all had cabins on the 8th deck. Maybe when “<u>my ship comes home</u>”—when I become rich I’ll be able to afford a cabin right up high...</p> </entry>
